Customer Experience Analytics for Online Food Ordering¶

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. The following questions need to be answered:

  1. What is the minimum, average, and maximum time it takes for food to be prepared once an order is placed?
  2. How many orders are not rated?
  3. Which are the top 5 restaurants in terms of the number of orders received?
  4. Which is the most popular cuisine on weekends?
  5. What percentage of the orders cost more than 20 dollars?
  6. What is the mean order delivery time?
  7. The company has decided to give 20% discount vouchers to the top 5 most frequent customers. Find the IDs of these customers and the number of orders they placed.
  8. The company wants to provide a promotional offer in the advertisement of the restaurants. The condition to get the offer is that the restaurants must have a rating count of more than 50 and the average rating should be greater than 4 Find the restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer.
  9. The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders.
  10. The company wants to analyze the total time required to deliver the food. What percentage of orders take more than 60 minutes to get delivered from the time the order is placed?
  11. The company wants to analyze the delivery time of the orders on weekdays and weekends. How does the mean delivery time vary during weekdays and weekends?
  12. What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business?

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Recommendations:¶

  • Work on getting the time to prepare and deliver an order to between 35 and 40 minutes
    • 30 minutes is the national standard
    • It should take 10 to 15 minutes to prepare an order
    • It should not take over 15 minutes to deliver an order
  • Start by working on the top four cusinie types getting the most orders:
    • American
    • Japanese
    • Italian
    • Chinese
  • Add drivers on weekends when demand is the highest
  • Consider restricting delivery area to speed the delivery time time
  • Work with the restaurant partners to improve food preparation time
  • Consider dropping the cuisine types with the least orders:
    • Southern 17 orders
    • Korean 13 orders
    • Spanish 12 orders
    • Vietnamese 7 orders
  • Work on increasing the number of repeat customers
    • Add incentives or giving discounts on future orders

Future considerations:¶

  • Add weather data to the analysis to determine if/how weather is affecting delivery times
  • Add time of day to the orders to detemine when the majority of orders are placed on the weekends
    • That is when drivers will be needed the most
  • Add geographic data to determine what areas of the city generate the most orders
    • Preposition drivers in those areas to be ready for the orders
  • Perform a deeper drive on the top four cuisine types to determine exact cost and profit for the deliveries
  • Perform sentament analysis on customer rating and reviews

Multivariate Analysis¶

Introduction¶

The instructions for this assignment stated the goal was to give suggestions on how the restaurants could enhance the customer experience. Before completing this question, did did some research on the internet for ways to better the customer experience when ordering food for delivery. I found the following four references and the main points in each:

  • How To Improve the Food Delivery Customer Experience (Door Dash)

    • https://get.doordash.com/en-us/blog/6-strategies-to-improve-customer-experience-with-food-delivery
    • Boost customer experience in restaurants with fast delivery
    • Offer special promotions & freebies
    • Analyze customer data

  • 6 Customer Experience Aspects That Any Food Delivery App Should Ensure

    • https://customerthink.com/6-customer-experience-aspects-that-any-food-delivery-app-should-ensure/
    • Real-time delivery tracking
    • Cross-Sale and Product Recommendations
    • Broad and Secure Payment Options

  • Online Food Delivery: Using Data to Measure and Improve Customer Service Experience

    • https://www.driveresearch.com/market-research-company-blog/online-food-delivery-using-data-to-measure-and-improve-customer-service-experience/
    • Delivery speed
    • Reviews and recommendations
    • Waiting times
    • Evaluate the Delivery Experience

  • Improving Customer Delivery Experiences (Grub Hub)

    • https://get.grubhub.com/blog/improving-customer-experience/ .
    • Make it Fast
      • 60% of delivery customers say timeliness is a key factor to their satisfaction.
    • Driver Support
      • Increase the amount of deliveries your drivers can make by finding the fastest routes, with alternates for rush hour. Or, outsource delivery to augment (or replace) your in-house drivers with an on-demand fleet.
    • Make It Accurate
    • Make it Easy
    • Make it Delicious
    • Make it Affordable

  • How to Provide an Unforgettable Food Delivery Experience to Your Customers (8 Ways)

    • https://startuptalky.com/food-delivey-customer-experience/
    • Deliver Good Quality Food
    • Timely Delivery
    • Treat Every Customer as a Unique Customer
    • Surprise Discount on Food - Who Doesnt Like It

  • Food Delivery Service Statistics That You Need to Know

    • https://beambox.com/food-delivery-service-statistics
    • A study revealed that Uber Eats was the fastest to the door with an average wait time of 35 minutes and 31 seconds from the point of order (QSR Magazine)
    • Postmates came second, averaging 40 minutes and 12 seconds (QSR Magazine)
    • In the same study, Grubhub was the slowest with an average wait time of 50 minutes and 22 seconds (QSR Magazine)

Across the first four articles, the one topic that is mentinoned in all is deliver speed. People want their food fast. In question 15, we determined how many restuarants take over 60 minutes to prepare and deliver an order. I also did an analysis for 35 and 40 minutes. Given the beambox.com article, the ideal delivery time is 35 to 40 minutes.

I am going to analyze which restuarants take the longest to prepare and deliver the order. Improving this will help with the customer experience.

I will also determine how many customers are repeat customers for each type of restaurant (cuisine type). Repeat customers is where restaurants make their money. Restaurants should target them with special offers and promotions.

The following section computes the total time to complete an order by cuisine type. This is to see if there is one or more cuisine type that is taking longer than any others. The data is computed for all days and then done for weekdays and weekends. This is to determine if and how much there is a diffence there is between the total time between weekdays and weekends. Weekends are busier than weekdays.

The results are printed and then graphed as I like to see both.

The following section computes how many repeat customer there are for each restaurant and the sum of there orders. This is to compute the percentage of sales for one off customers as opposed to repeat customers. The percentage is computed in a following section.

This is based on the addage that it is cheaper to keep a customer rather than get a new customers. Repeat business is also the life blood for any restaurant.

A create a DataFrame, order it by restaurant name and customer id, and then iterate over it to get the sum for the repeat customers. One off customers are marked as zero sum of orders and the dropped at the end of the code section. This was the easiest way to do it and used the native drop_duplicates function.

In [27]:
# create a dataframe to hold the summarized data 
custdf = {'customer_id' : [13], 'restaurant_name' : ['joes'], 'num_repeat' : [0], 'sum_order_cost' : [0], 'food_type' : ['Burgers'] }
custdf = pd.DataFrame(data=custdf)

# copy of the master dataframe and sort by customer id 
sortdf = df.copy()
sortdf.sort_values(['restaurant_name' , 'customer_id'], inplace=True, ascending=True)
sortdf.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

#  I am old fashined.  I like initializing variables before they are used. 
newcust = 0
oldcust = 0 
numrepeat = 0
sumorder = 0 
rownum = 1
lastrow = 0 

# iterate over the sortdf.  if the n customer_id equals the n-1 customer_id, then add the n cost_of_order to the 
# running order total.  if this is a first repetition (numrepeat == 0), the add the n-1 cost_of_the_order to the 
# running order total.  if a customer has ordered more than 2 times from a restaurant, then the dataframe will have
# an entry for the second and all subsequent orders.  this is handled in the next section. 
for index, row in sortdf.iterrows():
    newcust = row['customer_id'] 
    if newcust == oldcust: 
        if numrepeat == 0:
            numrepeat = 1 
            sumorder = oldorder  
        sumorder = sumorder + row['cost_of_the_order']
        numrepeat += 1     
    if numrepeat != 0 and newcust == oldcust: 
        to_append = [row['customer_id'], row['restaurant_name'], numrepeat, sumorder, row['cuisine_type']]
        custdf_length = len(custdf)
        custdf.loc[custdf_length] = to_append 
    if newcust != oldcust: 
        numrepeat = 0 
        sumorder = 0 
    oldcust = newcust
    oldorder = row['cost_of_the_order']

# using the drop.duplicates function to only keep the last order a customer placed if there were more than 2 orders. 
custdf.drop(0, axis=0, inplace=True)    #drop the first row that was used to initialize the series 
custdf.drop_duplicates(subset=['customer_id', 'restaurant_name'], keep='last', inplace=True)
custdf.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

print(custdf.head(10))
del sortdf     #free the memory.

This section computes the percentage of repeat orders as compared to total orders for each restaurant. How much did the a restaurant make from the repeat orders. I am show the top 20 as the bottom 20 will all be zero since they did not have any repeats.

In [34]:
# Create 2 dataframes containing the restaurant namme and sum of the order cost of the repeated orders (custdf)
# and another datafram containing the restaurant name and sum of all the orders for all restaurants 
# merge the dataframes by rows 
# replace all nan with zero as nan would indicate zero repeated orders 
# compute percentage of repeated orders to all orders and load into new column 

repeatdf = custdf.groupby(['restaurant_name'])['sum_order_cost'].sum()
alldf = df.groupby(['restaurant_name'])['cost_of_the_order'].sum()
profitdf = pd.concat([alldf , repeatdf], axis=1)
profitdf['sum_order_cost'] = profitdf['sum_order_cost'].replace(np.nan, 0)
profitdf['repeat_perc'] = 0.0
profitdf.reset_index(inplace=True)
profitdf['repeat_perc'] = (profitdf['sum_order_cost'] / profitdf['cost_of_the_order']) *100
profitdf.sort_values(by='repeat_perc', ascending=False).head(20)

tempdf=df.loc[(df['cost_of_the_order'] > 20.00) ]

Question 12: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business?¶

Conclusions:¶

  • The top four cusinie types getting the most orders are:
    • American
    • Japanese
    • Italian
    • Chinese
    • Together they account for 82.56% of all orders.
  • The cuisine types with the least orders are:
    • Southern
    • Korean
    • Spanish
    • Vietnamese
  • %71.18 of orders happen during the weekends
  • The majority of orders are between roughly 11 and 23 dollars.
    • Approximately 30% of orders cost more than 20 dollars
    • The majority of revenue comes from orders between 5 and 20 dollars
  • The average time to prepare and deliver an order is 52 minutes
    • Average of 24 minutes to prepare an order
    • Average 27 minutes to deliver it
  • 60% of delivery customers say timeliness is a key factor to their satisfaction. (from external source)
  • The cuisine type with longest time to prepare and deliver an order are the same as the ones getting the most orders
  • If there are repeat customers, they usually repeat 2 to 4 times with the majority (%69) repeating only 2 times
    • Customers are being lost
  • The long order times might be the reason why there are few repeat orders
    • It takes too long to get the food!

Recommendations:¶

  • Work on getting the time to prepare and deliver an order to between 35 and 40 minutes
    • 30 minutes is the national standard
    • It should take 10 to 15 minutes to prepare an order
    • It should not take over 15 minutes to deliver an order
  • Start by working on the top four cusinie types getting the most orders:
    • American
    • Japanese
    • Italian
    • Chinese
  • Add drivers on weekends when demand is the highest
  • Consider restricting delivery area to speed the delivery time time
  • Work with the restaurant partners to improve food preparation time
  • Consider dropping the cuisine types with the least orders:
    • Southern 17 orders
    • Korean 13 orders
    • Spanish 12 orders
    • Vietnamese 7 orders
  • Work on increasing the number of repeat customers
    • Add incentives or giving discounts on future orders

Future considerations:¶

  • Add weather data to the analysis to determine if/how weather is affecting delivery times
  • Add time of day to the orders to detemine when the majority of orders are placed on the weekends
    • That is when drivers will be needed the most
  • Add geographic data to determine what areas of the city generate the most orders
    • Preposition drivers in those areas to be ready for the orders
  • Perform a deeper drive on the top four cuisine types to determine exact cost and profit for the deliveries
  • Perform sentament analysis on customer rating and reviews
